INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (1,292,'Luis M Hernandez','luishernandez@greatbatchmedical.com','','12.30.230.138','2011-03-30 23:56:37','2011-03-30 23:56:37','Brian, I would like only to share with you a use I do with the SOFP, which is as follow:\n\nI try to match the SOFP to the Kaizen and Kaizen Costing we perform, this is very helpful since we match whatever the organization will make with the cost improvement/profit improvement it will make, is is very interesting how the in the same excercise you can understand and provide prompt feedback of the Capacity, NVA Processes, Cost and Revenue.\nbest regards',0,'1','','',0,0),(2,292,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','66.51.234.50','2011-03-31 11:48:12','2011-03-31 11:48:12','Luis:\nThank you for the comment. You are our first commentator on this new blog format :-)\n\nHave you tried to use the Lean Accouning box score within the SOFP process. It can be very helpful in presenting the information and enabling good decision-making.\n\nBrian',0,'1','','',0,2),(3,302,'Tom Buttross','teb11@psu.edu','','90.22.174.6','2011-06-18 02:05:45','2011-06-18 02:05:45','I realize most readers know the topic, but I would find it informative to have any acronyms, like SOFP, defined, either in the header of early in each blog post. Maybe it is the academic in me . : )',0,'1','','',0,0),(4,180,'James','jpradun@gmail.com','','204.28.3.51','2011-06-17 17:32:58','2011-06-17 17:32:58','We\'ve been doing this SOFP process for several years and in the COI phase.  The biggest challenge we find is actually adjusting the capacity for when business is up or down.  We don\'t quite trust our data and it doesn\'t \"feel\" right to cut or add overtime/employees as customer demand changes.  It seems like a simple fix to implement, but the fear of extending production lead times or being caught unprepared is difficult to overcome.  These aren\'t even drastic changes.  Sometimes it takes a leap of faith to believe your lean changes are working or that the forecast, by definition a guess, may actually be right.\n\nThanks for your blog entries.  It\'s good to see another perspective.',0,'1','','',0,0),(5,180,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','96.227.220.246','2011-06-22 11:43:13','2011-06-22 11:43:13','James:\nThanks for the comment. Are you with Watlow? We did a 5-day event a few weeks back on SOFP to bring some standardization and then to roll up SOFP to the enterprise level. There is a ton of work to do make the changes, and not the least is the capacity calculations. But I think that over the next few months this should work out.\nBrian',0,'1','','',0,2),(6,180,'LeanOperations.com','willislebron@zoho.com','http://www.leanoperations.com','94.14.14.181','2012-06-17 01:20:24','2012-06-17 01:20:24','I think this is among the most vital info for me.\nAnd i\'m glad reading your article. But want to remark on some general things, The website style is wonderful, the articles is really nice : D. Good job, cheers',0,'1','','',0,0),(7,2583,'Doug Webster','businessdr@hotmail.com','','173.66.47.184','2013-02-15 20:33:13','2013-02-15 20:33:13','You use an anecdotal reference to ABC product costing--an implementation that appears on its surface to be poorly implemented from a business needs perspective--to then generalize about ABC and product costing as an entire methodology.  Moreover, your discussion confuses ABC with standard costing.  These are totally separate concepts, as I imagine you know.  Certainly ABC can be used to develop standard costs and variances, and there are arguments pro and con for doing so.  However, this particular case offers no information to generalize to the conclusion that product costing is of no value.  Moreover, your third paragraph is titled \"ACTIVITY-BASED STANDARD PRODUCT COSTING\", as if this were some particular well recognized method.  You may not realize, however, that a Google search shows your comments above as the ONLY reference on the entire web to those 5 words in that order.  This makes my case that while there is product costing and standard costing, either of which can apply ABC, there is no standard approach, as you seem to imply, to Activity-based standard product costing. \n\nEach of your paragraphs would require much more discussion to get into details, and contrast the example from which you are trying to generalize to that which would typically be understood to be ABC best practices.  Perhaps the most telling part of this superficial analysis is the conclusion.  You started off trying to justify why product costing was unhelpful, and conclude it is because because this company implemented standard costing in a manner that was burdensom?  Really?  That is the basis of your conclusion?  I suggest you review the difference between standard costing and product costing, and choose one or the other (or both independently) to refute.  Using a poor example of one to refute the other makes no sense at all.',0,'1','','',0,0),(8,2583,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','72.94.195.239','2013-02-15 23:51:41','2013-02-15 23:51:41','Doug: Thanks for your message and thoughtful comments. This blog is anecdotal and I was not trying to give a detailed explanation. The blog was also in response to some rather offensive criticism I received because of my lack of enthusiasm for ABC. As I mentioned in the blog, I am speaking here about companies that are aspiring to create a lean culture within their organizations. I am sure there are many valuable uses of activity-based methods, but lean companies is not one.\nI apologize if my descriptions are sloppy. It has been 15 or more years since I have used ABC/M and I may be out of touch. But, I have worked with many companies that have a similar profile to the one described in the blog. These companies do use ABC method to calculate their product costs and they go into the Standard Cost field in the ERP system. This particular company is a fine organization and very much respected through out the world for more than 100 years. If their accounting systems were audited using one if the ABC/M  assessments, they would achieve a high score. They would not told they had poorly implemented the methods. These approaches to ABC are very harmful to lean organization. They are deeply anti-lean.\nBut, having said all this, you are right. Forgive me. I was writing a populist blog, not an academic treatise. I was trying to get my point across by using some mockery and irony.\nAll the best, brian',0,'1','','',0,2),(9,304,'Ieva verslo sistemos','ievarats@gmail.com','http://www.verslovaldymosistemos.lt','88.216.168.7','2012-07-03 07:49:26','2012-07-03 07:49:26','Well but one thing is obvious - great quality cost much more either way, especially for businesses but there\'s humanity factor - not to produce junk.',0,'1','','',0,0),(10,307,'Griff Coxey','coxey@dishmail.net','','70.41.63.108','2012-07-20 02:31:06','2012-07-20 02:31:06','You are preaching to the choir my friend. I an waiting for the opportunity to spread the Lean Accounting gospel.',0,'1','','',0,0),(11,315,'Nitin','nitin.shrotri@solutionsline.com','','122.169.79.161','2012-05-03 06:22:53','2012-05-03 06:22:53','I have experience of implementing Lean Manufacturing &amp; It is truly said , It should be Business Strategy and not only shop floor tool.',0,'1','','',0,0),(12,315,'Stuart Rosenberg','rosen-cost-acct@comcast.net','','24.0.89.124','2012-05-03 15:56:15','2012-05-03 15:56:15','I could not agree with the premise.  I have been involved in a number of Lean implementations.  However, management only sought to implement on the manufacturing floor instead of company wide.  One of the fears with Lean was with inventory.  I find the \'fear\' in people\'s minds was that Lean means they would not have enough inventory on hand to meet customers demand.  Lean inventory actually means having \'the right amount of inventory at the right time\'.  Fail to change attitude and grasp the ideas of Inventory Optimization or Right Sizing Inventory.  Whatever savings they gather from the manufacturing floor is then eaten up by the carrying investment of excess inventory.',0,'1','','',0,0),(13,315,'Matthew Hopkins','M_hopkins@live.co.uk','','86.31.201.110','2012-05-05 08:06:03','2012-05-05 08:06:03','At first I disagreed that lean was a money making strategy. I believed it is more than that as it plays a huge role in the engagement of the workforce. A little more thought and if a lean business system didn\'t make more money then the CEO would be implementing a strategy that is not in the interests of his shareholders. I now see it more simply that all these other answers people give are the drivers of becoming more profitable.\n\nThe problem is however, too often lean is not implemented as a company wide culture. Its not driven at the highest levels as the shareholders do not often have the patience for lean. If many people were offered two machines; one massive one that produced 10,000 per day and a comparatively much smaller machine that took less time to setup but only produced 6,000 a day, then they would pick the big inflexible machine which is essentially a decision that will be made by finance to satisfy the \"efficiency\" desired by the shareholders.',0,'1','','',0,0),(14,315,'Irene','irene.abrisqueta@gmail.com','','119.6.108.86','2012-05-16 03:31:25','2012-05-16 03:31:25','I agree that the scope of lean is beyond the shop floor, although I disagree with the statement \"lean is a business strategy to make money\".\n\nI consider lean as a philosophy (a system of principles for guidance) rather than a strategy (a plan of action to achieve long-term vision), meaning that the philosophy doesn\'t change regardless of any change in Top Management whereas a strategy might. You may chose to follow one strategy or the other according to what best fit your long-term vision, as long as you stay true to your principles. Also, \"making money\" is a consequence. If you define lean as a business strategy to make money, you are implying that lean doesn\'t fit non-profit organizations.\n\nHaving said that, I see how that definition is appealing to Top Management and can encourage them to learn more about lean... and most of the time that is exactly what we want!',0,'1','','',0,0),(15,315,'Griff Coxey','coxey@dishmail.net','','70.41.63.108','2012-07-20 02:24:38','2012-07-20 02:24:38','Great stuff Nick. Here in WI  most companies THINK Lean is what the Leaning Tower of Pisa does, at least as far as their accounting department is concerned. I put the word Lean principles in the search for ALL accounting jobs in WI on a website and Found ONE in the entire state. This is proof to me that Lean is not the business strategy of these companies. How can it be if the bean-counters are not on board ?\nCompanies here say they are LEAN but they have monster ERP systems, standard cost systems where they are chasing ghosts(variances) all the time, and complicated reporting mechanisms where they are more concerned with finding people who can use pivot tables and macros than people who can simplify processes, eliminate waste, create value for the customer, and most importantly, help them make money. \nTrying to combine Lean manufacturing with traditional accounting is definitely like trying to put a square peg in a round hole. \"It ain\'t gonna work.\"',0,'1','','',0,0),(16,325,'Ron Ferro','rrferro@aol.com','','68.208.127.1','2012-05-17 16:56:11','2012-05-17 16:56:11','Since companies have abandoned standard costing, how do lean companies value their products, or determine product line profitability?',0,'1','','',0,0),(17,325,'Brian Maskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','96.227.250.78','2012-05-18 13:52:28','2012-05-18 13:52:28','Ron:\nI will give you the quick and easy answer, but I am sure there is a lot more needed - particularly if you are new to lean. The first issue is that we are not at all interested in \"margins\" based on fully absorbed costs because the calculation of the costs (by standard cost, ABC, or any other absorption method) distort the reality. But we are very interested in the contribution margin. This is the price less the variable costs. The variable costs are generally the costs of materials and the costs of any outside processing required to make and/or deliver the product. We not NOT consider labor or machine time to be variable because it stays the same irrespective of what you sell - at least for the medium term.\n\nContribution margin tells you some thing real and important - how much cash is this product, sales order, customer, region, etc.  bringing into the company.\n\nThe second issue is much more lean related. We are not overly interested in the profitability of individual products, but we are very interested in the profitability of the value stream. We collect, control, reduce, and improve operations and their related spending through the value streams. Once again, this is real. We know who works in the value stream, how much materials we buy, etc. etc. We also know the value stream revenue. So the profitability and cash income of a value stream is real information that is used by the value stream manager to improve his/her operation and outcomes. \n\nWe avoid the allocation of costs to the value streams. We are interested in the real, actual direct costs - although inevitably some allocation is needed, but we minimize it because it is difficult to control allocated costs. Plus it requires accountants to do work that is waste. But we never allocate \"overheads\" into value streams because they will cause the distortions I mentioned above.\n\nMake sense?\n\nBrian Maskell\nbmaskell@maskell.com',0,'1','','',0,0),(18,325,'Griff Coxey','coxey@dishmail.net','','70.41.63.108','2012-07-24 01:09:29','2012-07-24 01:09:29','Excellent comment Brian &amp; Nick. One of my credos is \"The paperwork must match the process. \" ALSO, regarding labor. We got to the point where we told our Plant Manager; \n\" I don\'t care how many temps you use, how much overtime you work, whatever. As long as you maintain quality and throughput you have 6% of sales for Production(value-added) labor. No more chasing variances and feeding the software BEAST. \nGuess what: Our throughput immediately went up and our Production Labor as a % of sales went down.',0,'1','','',0,0),(19,329,'Griff Coxey','coxey@dishmail.net','','70.41.63.108','2012-07-24 01:13:50','2012-07-24 01:13:50','Where can one find a company that wants this Lean CFO ? The standard here in Wisconsin seems to be \"complex measurement systems that no one understands. \"',0,'1','','',0,0),(20,337,'Griff Coxey','coxey@dishmail.net','','70.41.63.108','2012-07-24 00:58:17','2012-07-24 00:58:17','Good stuff Nick.  Sounds a lot like we did at Wind Mill. What you describe is quite simple and much more valuable than chasing ghosts(variance analysis) and preparing complicated reports that normally no one outside of the preparer understands.',0,'1','','',0,0),(21,348,'Dave Kilbourn','dbkmba@sbcglobal.net','','12.156.136.194','2012-10-26 20:37:00','2012-10-26 20:37:00','Excellent article.  I like these bite-sized informative papers.',0,'1','','',0,0),(22,368,'Brian Mackenzii','rdwhtblumack@yahoo.com','','50.50.180.2','2012-10-31 00:44:18','2012-10-31 00:44:18','Nick,\nGreat insight, as always, in basic and understandable terms for improving things at the front lines.',0,'1','','',0,0),(23,374,'Michael Bremer','michael@cumberlandchicago.com','http://www.cumberlandchicago.com','24.15.21.157','2012-11-18 17:55:20','2012-11-18 17:55:20','Good summary of the room Brian.  The best cell information boards and management Obeya type boards or rooms should go through several iterations as people who use the board(s) come together for decision making.  I have seen a tendency to put too much information on these boards.  If people are not using the information for decision making on a routine basis, that info probably should not be on the board.  It can be kept off-line.  Information boards should be looked at as an experiment.  And over a three to six month period the info shown should evolve.  That evolution is key to keeping these things fresh and useful.\nBest wishes,\nMichael Bremer\nAuthor \"Escape the Improvement Trap\"',0,'1','','',0,0),(24,374,'Stephan Hartman','Stephan.hartman@rexnord.com','','31.149.47.229','2012-11-26 10:24:37','2012-11-26 10:24:37','Hi Brian,\n\nI like the obeya room and have seen some nice examples in practice. The only thing I have not figured out yet is how to use the concept with team members on different locations (worldwide). Do you have ideas?\n\nThanks, Stephan',0,'1','','',0,0),(25,374,'Brett Griffiths','brett@LTSLEAN.com','http://www.leantransitionsolutions.com','86.177.81.171','2012-11-26 18:18:51','2012-11-26 18:18:51','Hi Brian\nGreat piece of work, I have the same concept here in the UK but the problem is all the funded training and development work is Shop-floor led and not good for Hoshin Kanri led. Major challenge to the way the government is funding Lean projects.\nCheers \n\nBrett',0,'1','','',0,0),(26,374,'Angelo Gerada','angelo_gerada@europe.bd.com','','80.254.147.52','2012-12-11 09:38:07','2012-12-11 09:38:07','Do you know of any training courses of Obeya room facilitation, as this is something that is interesting me and something I would like to introduce into my company?',0,'1','','',0,0),(27,374,'Vidya','krishnanvidya@gmail.com','','117.192.229.254','2013-03-22 14:19:54','2013-03-22 14:19:54','Crisp and concise Obeya description..  its a classic combination of Lean Strategy and PDCA cycle.. Two very important requisites to ensure the success of this tool is 1.Managers/group should to be prepared in advance for discussing issues in War room, and not to be said - Leadership commitment, which if missing loses the whole purpose of the exercise.',0,'1','','',0,0),(28,374,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','72.94.195.239','2013-03-22 15:01:38','2013-03-22 15:01:38','Vidya:\nYes. It all comes down to good leadership. If the leadership do not buy-in in an authentic way, then little can be achieved. Bu t wen they do .....  Obeya Rooms are wonderfully effective. It is great to see it.\nAll the best,\nBrian',0,'1','','',27,2),(29,374,'Brian Maskell','Bmaskell@maskell.com','http://Www.maskell.com','71.246.7.165','2014-01-13 18:18:22','2014-01-13 18:18:22','Angela:\nA while back you put a comment against a blog I wrote on Obeya rooms. You said you hoped to introduce Obeya into your company.\nI was just wondering if you made the progress you hoped to make.\nLet me know -when you have a minute.\nBrian',0,'1','','',26,0),(30,374,'Chris Turner','chris@radical-transformation.com','http://leanmfgonline.com','96.39.179.147','2014-05-26 17:05:45','2014-05-26 17:05:45','Hi Brian, \n\nGreat introduction to Obeya. Interesting how many people believe they are actually doing lean, and yet, they don\'t have an integrated infrastructure to support their efforts. Obeya is the place where lean principles are turned into daily, weekly and monthly rites and rituals. It only becomes true \"Just in Time\" when a company can perform and improve as easily as getting up every morning and brushing your teeth, or taking a shower. These are our personal daily rites and rituals that everyone takes for granted. Obeya is the path to doing the same with lean principles!',0,'1','','',0,0),(31,392,'Callye Keen','ckeen@kform.com','http://www.kform.com','69.17.56.242','2012-12-03 17:17:07','2012-12-03 17:17:07','The traditional concept of indirect labor cost can really hamper finding value. If you are distributing indirect costs across all processes or products, a business masks success and failure. You may have a value stream that is incredibly profitable but false overhead costs hide success by absorbing costs from losing value streams. This problem also results in a lack of true focus in Kaizen selection and measurement.',0,'1','','',0,0),(32,402,'Oscar Delgado','oscardelgado5@yahoo.com.mx','','187.131.161.91','2012-11-30 15:33:15','2012-11-30 15:33:15','Excelent job ! I will wait your next blog: virtual obeya room.',0,'1','','',0,0),(33,402,'Edward Wolf','carbonatom@mail.com','','68.202.214.58','2012-11-30 21:54:16','2012-11-30 21:54:16','Hello Brian, I enjoy your posts as they tend to be more advanced / wider in scope. The Obeya room part 2 mentions the Virtual Obeya room. I agree this has a lot of value for multi plant locations (Using the company server / files or the Cloud). Smaller companies that have more than one location need this as a necessity. Having had to create data trackers in the cloud, it would be nice to have a basic editable foot-print to work off of so we take into consideration the latest basics. If it had sequential flow guidance that matched some of the latest training and possibly even prompted these entries, you can standardize an effective customizable tool for executives to guide their companies. Now that I am in fantasy land I will stop. Thanks again for your posts.\nFYI - As you are likely aware, Google has a Fusion Table for collaborative Data Gathering.\nRegards.',0,'1','','',0,0),(34,402,'Daniel Breston','daniel.breston@qriosity-managingit.com','','82.26.5.9','2014-12-26 14:30:49','2014-12-26 14:30:49','Hi Brian\n\nAre you ready to tell us more?\n\nDaniel',0,'1','','',32,0),(35,432,'Md Faizul Haque','huq_faiz@yahoo.com','','115.127.10.58','2012-12-10 12:15:08','2012-12-10 12:15:08','Dear. Its a good and important issues to all the organization. I am very much interested to the Blanch sheet and approaches  for conventional and Lean accounting',0,'1','','',0,0),(36,432,'Md Faizul Haque','huq_faiz@yahoo.com','','115.127.10.58','2012-12-10 12:46:40','2012-12-10 12:46:40','Dear. Its a good and very important issues to the all organization. I am so much interested to get the Balance sheet and approaches to the Lean accounting and conventional accting from you. Faiz',0,'1','','',0,0),(37,432,'Ryelandt','info@img-consult.org','http://www.img-consult.org','109.128.23.14','2012-12-11 08:35:46','2012-12-11 08:35:46','Dear Brian,\nI appreciate your comments. I am busy now coaching a Finance departement improve their process.\nYour third reason explaining why often a company doesn\'t consider LEAN in the accounting area could be explained/reformulated this way: Trainings on Lean are focusing mainly on the activities in the operations (shopfloor/Logistics). Case studies used for training \"avoid\" the other departments.  As a consequence there is no inspiration/understanding/willingness to risk any Lean project in Finance or other \"Supporting department (M. Porter\'s definition)\".',0,'1','','',0,0),(38,432,'Maheswar Bodiga','bodiga.maheswar@voith.com','http://www.voith.com','203.126.24.142','2012-12-12 04:06:25','2012-12-12 04:06:25','Very eager to follow Lean Accounting, we have already implemented Lean Manufacturing at our unit but could not implement lean accounting.',0,'1','','',0,0),(39,432,'Mark','vat_checker@yahoo.com','http://vat-number-validation.eu/lean-accounting/','78.9.2.206','2014-08-09 09:39:43','2014-08-09 09:39:43','Thank you for the detailed and simple explanation.\nMark',0,'1','','',0,0),(40,457,'Robert Simonis','rsimonis@lear.com','http://www.lear.com','165.207.0.100','2012-12-17 19:57:36','2012-12-17 19:57:36','Brian,\n\nAs always, thank you for educating us all.\n\nRegards,\n\nRobert',0,'1','','',0,0),(41,457,'Karen Broyles','karen.broyles@biomerieux.com','','104.129.196.59','2015-09-30 19:19:37','2015-09-30 19:19:37','Brian,\nYou worked with me and Bill Kerber at Sunnen back in 2007 on lean accounting.  You provided a lot of insight that helped us in our lean journey.  I am now doing lean work at Bio Merieux and am having difficulties convincing the finanacial guy on site about the benefits of lean.  When I told him that we were going to increase volume and not have to proporitonaly increase the costs that standard costing would assume and therefore show an impact to COGS.  He disagreed that standard costing assumes that as you increase sales units of a product that the costs are assumed to increase proportionately which was one of the key concepts you trained us on.  Do you have any supporting material to help me show this?',0,'1','','',0,0),(42,474,'dan','danielstitt4@gmail.com','','50.147.148.66','2012-12-22 13:38:29','2012-12-22 13:38:29','It is really all about being able to plan a company path that relates time, progress, and value gained and then following that path. The problem is that plans are predictions and managers hate to be held to predictions. It is the same problem at the budget (high) level or the production/project (detail) level.',0,'1','','',0,0),(43,474,'M. James Allen, Ph.D. Finance','james.allen@leandiagnostics.com','http://www.leandiagnostics.com','71.194.154.50','2012-12-23 03:05:36','2012-12-23 03:05:36','Nice work! Can\'t wait for your subsequent blogs... Jim',0,'1','','',0,0),(44,474,'Larry Maggio, CPIM CSC','lmaggio@rochester.rr.com','http://www.apicsr.org','74.69.72.104','2012-12-23 11:29:36','2012-12-23 11:29:36','Nick,\nGreat lead in for Part 1. We are looking forward to Part 2!\nLarry',0,'1','','',0,0),(45,474,'Ron Ferro','rrferro@aol.com','','50.128.229.56','2013-01-02 03:47:38','2013-01-02 03:47:38','All these management tools are basic to any on-going operation or enterprise regardless if it uses historical costing, budget, trend analysis or forecasting. I do not see how these tools are any different in lean accounting. I look forward to your next blog.\nOne essential element not covered in your blog. That is analysis of the Supply Chain, mainly purchase order approval and tracking. In project management, this essential analysis and tracking remains key to determining the progress of the project, project cash flow, and freed funds. Determination when to spend and when to defer expenditures provide high visibility to all levels of management.\nSo far all the white papers, the bad mouthing of present management tools compared to lean accounting for lean manufacturing have been only smoke and mirrors. No real substance, another marketing gimmick to create demand for services.',0,'1','','',0,0),(46,474,'Melisa','mocca_ice2002@yahoo.com','','175.140.162.140','2013-11-11 13:55:57','2013-11-11 13:55:57','It really bring a lot value to read your blog. I am just learning on the lean accounting and it was brilliant idea in my mind after reading your article. Thanks a lot.',0,'1','','',0,0),(47,482,'Mike Govan','mgovan2000@yahoo.com','','199.231.50.135','2013-01-03 18:47:00','2013-01-03 18:47:00','As a journeyman cost accountant.....Great article.....this is the only way to survive!',0,'1','','',0,0),(48,495,'dan','danielstitt4@gmail.com','','50.147.148.66','2012-12-28 14:46:47','2012-12-28 14:46:47','Excellent! The term value has to be present to understand the stream.',0,'1','','',0,0),(49,495,'Patrick Phillips','patrick@patrickphillips.org','http://leantechnologytransformation.blogspot.com/','71.195.194.174','2013-01-01 04:50:46','2013-01-01 04:50:46','Wow, great post.  Thank you for sharing.',0,'1','','',0,0),(50,513,'deepak kumar','d_deepak555@rediffmail.com','http://linkedin','117.207.0.222','2013-01-06 14:47:15','2013-01-06 14:47:15','Great Information,\nIt helps to clear the wastage,the way we shall think &amp; approach to our tasks n plans.\n\nDeepak',0,'1','','',0,0),(51,513,'DJ Duarte','dduarte@kaizen.com','','14.136.144.40','2013-01-17 02:33:28','2013-01-17 02:33:28','Great read and spot on!  For whatever reason, many companies can\'t seem to break that mold until they fail in attempting to link traditional and lean metrics, or even worse collect both in isolation without any comparison.  I see it all the time.  Looking forward to the next blog.  Thanks.',0,'1','','',0,0),(52,543,'Marc Gilson','marc.gilson@wanadoo.fr','','86.200.152.73','2013-01-21 08:57:28','2013-01-21 08:57:28','About HR favoring individualism and self-interest, I totally agree with your comment. I have seen the \"Personal Performance Plan\" counter-productive and not favoring employees who like to cooperate and share information. The philosophy of domination of the fittest strenghten competition and conflicts between people. Young generation seems to be tougher than the preceeding ones.',0,'1','','',0,0),(53,559,'Robert Baird','robert.baird@leanteamsusa.com','http://leanteamsusa.com','68.81.41.19','2013-02-01 15:01:16','2013-02-01 15:01:16','This is really another example of leadership providing self serving decisions. As you point out they are not customer driven decisions and it always hurts the organization in the end. The cost in loss of revenue from the continuous month, quarter, and year end discounts are extreme but never added up?',0,'1','','',0,0),(54,559,'Bill Gilbert','wgilbert@bellsouth.net','','75.143.231.130','2013-02-02 22:02:02','2013-02-02 22:02:02','When I first began to practice Lean in the late 1980’s (we called it JIT at that time), I rearranged manufacturing into cells. Lead times immediately went from weeks to hours. When I approached the CEO about reducing finished goods inventories, the VP of Finance jumped in and said “we can’t afford to do that since the reduced production will kill our production variances”. This was a pharmaceutical company with 70% margins who never looked at the balance sheet. The inventories stayed.\n\nI later went to a medical device company and discovered a leased warehouse filled with aging sub-assemblies. When I inquired as to why this inventory existed, I was told that the existing VP of manufacturing had built this inventory during the 1991 economic slowdown to keep the manufacturing variances looking good. He had been hailed as a hero at the time. Needless to say the inventory and the leased warehouse continued to gather dust.',0,'1','','',0,0),(55,559,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','72.94.195.239','2013-02-02 22:38:52','2013-02-02 22:38:52','Bill:\nFor me it was the early \'90s and working with companies doing \"just-in-time\" manufacturing. There we three companies that cancelled their (what we now call) lean improvements because the operational numbers and financial reports we showing bad results when good lean things were happening. \n\nWith a background in both engineering and accounting, I recognized that traditional accounting is an enemy of lean transformation. This does not mean that traditional accounting is bad and wrong. But it does mean that it is UNSUITABLE for lean organizations. These days we have Lean Accounting that solves these problems, and replaces the old stuff. \n\nBut as is shown by GM and Chrysler - both companies are purported to be working with lean - there are still many companies that continue to slavishly use these damaging methods. It\'s like buying one of their cars and hitching up with dray horses.\n\nBrian',0,'1','','',54,2),(56,559,'Rob Green','roba.green@energizer.com','','71.255.140.154','2013-02-28 16:49:02','2013-02-28 16:49:02','Excellent article, do you see a difference on the standard costing bad habits between publicly held company and privately held companies?  I would think that it \"could\" be better at privately held companies because there wouldn\'t be the outside pressures of Wall Street.  I am currently a part of a publically held company, but will be moving to a private company in the near future.  Would appreciate anyone\'s experiences..',0,'1','','',0,0),(57,559,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','46.14.253.241','2013-02-28 22:19:42','2013-02-28 22:19:42','Rob:\nWhen it comes to Lean I think private companies do much better the public. I expect there is a lot of reasons fir this, and the ones you mentioned are important ones.\n But ... I think it all comes back to the leadership. The most important issue is the active commitment and driving of lean across the company.\nBrian',0,'1','','',56,2),(58,559,'Marc Gilson','marc.gilson@outlook.com','','86.200.158.67','2013-07-09 15:14:12','2013-07-09 15:14:12','Excellent examples. As a Division Controller, I have seen many times bad behaviours linked to these silly variance maximizations, and especially the absorption one.',0,'1','','',0,0),(59,559,'Angelo Cusinato','angelo@resourceplus.com','','173.161.33.77','2014-01-15 15:34:03','2014-01-15 15:34:03','Another example of a tool that is used by people that \n&gt; do not understand or  \n&gt; understand enough to use the flaw to maximize their short term bonus.',0,'1','','',0,0),(60,559,'Alexander Kudasov','kudasoff@rambler.ru','','95.30.107.124','2015-05-22 22:51:10','2015-05-22 22:51:10','Interesting article, but please take into account that vast number of companies also have such KPI as working capital which includes inventory so it\'s not so straightforward with negative side of overheads absorption as a method itself.',0,'1','','',0,0),(61,559,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','173.49.122.238','2015-05-23 08:06:19','2015-05-23 08:06:19','Alexander:\nYou have raised the right issue. This post is an extreme example that if we use traditional measurements like overhead absorption or working capital, our lean strategy will fail.\nBrian',0,'1','','',60,2),(62,559,'Marc Gilson','marc.gilson@outlook.com','','86.209.104.94','2015-11-25 10:19:47','2015-11-25 10:19:47','Yes you are right, but experience has shown me that when contradictory managers favor short term profit instead of KPIs !',0,'1','','',60,0),(63,721,'Marc Gilson','marc.gilson@outlook.com','','86.194.221.141','2013-03-06 13:45:59','2013-03-06 13:45:59','As finance manager in the industry for 24 years, I can confirm that GAAP have forced to put a part of fixed costs into the inventory valuation, triggering wrong operational decisions as increasing production without having received more orders from customers. I would advise to disconnect GAAP accounting from lean accounting. GAAP accounting comes from accountants to fulfill tax requirements. Its logic is far from the business point of view, hence the distortion between accountants and operational people!',0,'1','','',0,0),(64,799,'Stuart Rosenberg','rosen-cost-acct@comcast.net','','68.32.190.21','2013-03-11 13:55:46','2013-03-11 13:55:46','Interesting article. Just have a couple of questions:\n\n1- Why doesn\'t the cycle time include calculations for the 7 wastes?\n2- How are you measuring how much the 7 wastes are impeding the capacity?\n3- If interested in actual capacity, surely can not omit the 7 wastes from being observable and bench marked?',0,'1','','',0,0),(65,799,'NKatko','information@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','74.131.135.201','2013-05-02 13:07:21','2013-05-02 13:07:21','Stuart,\n1. Nonproductive capacity is the average time the value stream spends on the 7 wastes per the current state value stream map\n2. Productive capacity is the average time the value stream spends on value-added activities',0,'1','','',64,3),(66,867,'Scott Hoepfl','scott.hoepfl@gmail.com','','50.9.93.3','2013-03-28 22:37:11','2013-03-28 22:37:11','Receivers done on the wrong contract/blanket PO release\n\nUndocumented return to supplier transactions\n\nRequisitions/POs coded to the wrong Natural Account at creation',0,'1','','',0,0),(67,867,'Roy Sonday','rsonday@tampabay.rr.com','','97.96.41.213','2013-03-30 12:06:05','2013-03-30 12:06:05','Credit terms given are different than agreed upon.  \n\nShipping terms given are different than agreed upon.\n\nUnit of measure differences.',0,'1','','',0,0),(68,867,'M. James Allen','james.allen@leandiagnostics.com','http://www.leandiagnostics.com','75.15.12.200','2013-04-01 21:07:28','2013-04-01 21:07:28','Too many steps in the cash-to-cash cycle.\n\nToo much complexity in the p/n, cost, and overhead codes.\n\nJust a couple of thoughts off the top of my balding head. :) Jim',0,'1','','',0,0),(69,867,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','72.94.195.239','2013-04-01 21:44:44','2013-04-01 21:44:44','Jim, Scott, Roy:\n\nThank you for your contributions. We have had a bunch more from others too. I will collate them and move to the next step.\n\nBrian',0,'1','','',0,2),(70,867,'Dave Yaeger','Dave_yaeger@praxair.com','','192.151.110.230','2013-04-26 20:18:54','2013-04-26 20:18:54','Receiving  timely has always been the # 1 reason for delays in 3 way matching.  So we challenged why we have to receive.  We determined for inventory items we need to receive and some could move to ERS which is 2 way.  For non-inventory, we eliminated the formal receiving process.  Instead we image the invoice and send out two different emails to the requisitioner with the image link.  1. If invoice is below our $ treshold we will pay on terms unless you tell us not to. 2. If invoice is above $ threshold you must stamp OK to pay in imaging system.  This process was approved many years ago from external auditors and has run smoothly ever since.  Sales and Use taxes are also reasons for problems.  We solved this by using Vertex with our ERP system.',0,'1','','',0,0),(71,879,'Arnold Howe','a.r.howe@talktalk.net','','92.22.198.212','2013-04-18 11:48:59','2013-04-18 11:48:59','Illustration: the product we produce AB 123 needs 18 4mm dia 30mm long cap head screws per our product. At the moment we order these in boxes of 1000 as required. We use A 3 way verification system to approve payment of invoice.\nProposal: supplier provides and maintains stock direct to the production line to a level he thinks appropriate for them at their cost. We advise the supplier how many AB 123 have been produced that month and the supplier multiplies that Number by 18 and sends in his invoice which we pay Monthly.',0,'1','','',0,0),(72,879,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','41.139.135.138','2013-04-18 11:53:31','2013-04-18 11:53:31','Excellent Arnold. Thanks for the comment.\nUnder your approach how could to also eliminate the invoice?\nBrian',0,'1','','',71,2),(73,879,'Arnold Howe','a.r.howe@talktalk.net','','92.22.198.212','2013-04-18 12:25:58','2013-04-18 12:25:58','Yes, good idea. We could pay the supplier of the cap head screws based on our reported output of our AB 123. \nTrust is what paying for this procedure; operator doesn\'t steal screws, supplier is trusting us to report output/sales of AB 123 honestly.',0,'1','','',0,0),(74,879,'ed grinde','ed.grinde@yahoo.com','','12.156.202.230','2013-04-18 15:14:01','2013-04-18 15:14:01','Under this methodology, how will you reconcile any differneces between what the supplier thinks should be in inventory vs what is actually in inventory?  Of course, this is not a problem to the manufacturer IF the supplier takes responsibility/the risk of any shortages, lost parts, or parts damaged in production.  But if the supplier will not assume that risk, how much time will be spent analyzing and reconciling the inventory levels?',0,'1','','',0,0),(75,879,'CheeKin Tang','cktang68@yahoo.com','','192.86.100.76','2013-04-19 19:35:50','2013-04-19 19:35:50','Perhaps the same workflow that generates the data on monthly production could also trigger a workflow to process payment for the screws based on the # of AB 123 produced x 18 x price per screw (+ any additional screws used because of quality issues in producing AB 123, hopefully few).',0,'1','','',0,0),(76,879,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','92.25.3.231','2013-04-20 11:31:31','2013-04-20 11:31:31','Tang:\nAre you suggesting that they backflushing the materials needed to make the products through to the accounts payable so that the supplier gets paid based on what is used in production?\nBrian',0,'1','','',0,2),(77,879,'CheeKin Tang','cktang68@yahoo.com','','71.163.74.133','2013-04-20 15:02:29','2013-04-20 15:02:29','I am a novice with backflush costing. So, I am wondering if my suggestion can eliminate the invoice from the supplier. If so, perhaps it is something that can be considered. What do you think? Doable?\n\nI think in a high trust vendor-customer relationship, there may be a lot of opportunities for info sharing and working together to eliminate duplication of effort.',0,'1','','',76,0),(78,879,'Arnold Howe','a.r.howe@talktalk.net','','92.22.166.226','2013-04-26 11:39:21','2013-04-26 11:39:21','Ed, the supplier takes the risk and that is reflected in his price. There are costs and risks in this cost saving device, but I guess under the old system we ran out of stock and had to pay excess on transport charges etc etc.',0,'1','','',74,0),(79,879,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','86.40.43.208','2013-04-26 14:00:43','2013-04-26 14:00:43','Arnold:\nThe trust issue is simplified if we hold very low inventory and pull in new material every day. Any significant theft would create a production shortage that would reveal the problem. Also if you use a visual system of replenishment, the person responsible for the items would quickly identify the shortage.\n\nI know Johnny Cash stole a Cadillac \"one piece at a time\". But he had to wait a very ling time for him car :-))\nBrian',0,'1','','',73,2),(80,879,'Madhava krishna','madhav@skilglobal.com','http://www.skilglobal.com','146.185.28.61','2015-05-13 07:00:35','2015-05-13 07:00:35','Hi all,\n\nI could recollect the famous camera based (Dynamic visual inventory update to vendor) Kanban system used at world famous automobile to avoid this problem. \nVendor send products based on what he sees in the display screen.\n\nIt is similar to what Arnold Howe has suggested in his comment.\n\nBilling is done based on the parts that goes in the final assembly. (Day production report). Invoicing,payment and all related errors were poka-yoked. Awesome Idea.',0,'1','','',0,0),(81,894,'Donna Samuel','donna.samuel@sapartners.com','http://www.sapartners.com','88.98.33.225','2013-04-26 14:40:46','2013-04-26 14:40:46','I totally agree with the argument you make here. Convetional costing is the greatest inihibitor to improvement efforts. The only point I would make is to question the assertion that standard costing works OK in manufacturing companies. I agree that it was fine when the biggest costs were labour and capital. However, in most modern manufacturing companies, overhead represent such a huge proportion of overall costs that ill conceived product costs leads to misguided decision-making.',0,'1','','',0,0),(82,950,'Eric','eric.d.grey@gmail.com','','66.65.52.58','2013-05-13 12:49:27','2013-05-13 12:49:27','The root cause of longer than desired \"Get back Home\" time is subtly suggested in this post.  Inventory.  You have too much inventory if you have to wait for your bag on the belt.  The wait in Immigration sometimes masks the wait for your bag.\nEarly in my career traveling for work I realized that all that baggage slowed me down.  Literally -running through ATL with your bags praying you make it to recheck your bag AND your flight isn\'t fun.\nBut to your point in the post the value in this improvement is in that you have removed an excuse from the system.  You can\'t use the old \"immigration was slow\" excuse anymore.  The spotlight is now firmly on the inventory issue.\nWhile more seasoned practitioners know that you need to look at the whole, sometimes getting rid of the highly visible but less consequential problem actually helps the team.  The distraction is removed and the focus on the root cause can begin.  As the team reflects they\'ll self-realize the value of root cause thinking.  \"I figured it out\" is much better than \"you told me so\".\nWith all that said, with carry-ons AND Global Entry I\'ve managed to get through JFK in 10 minutes, LAX in less than 10, ATL takes longer only because getting to the rentals means gong through the airport.',0,'1','','',0,0),(83,950,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','71.185.250.133','2013-05-13 13:08:17','2013-05-13 13:08:17','Eric:\nExcellent point. I had not thought about luggage as inventory. Great comment. \nYou are right. I do not travel light. I have just yesterday returned from a 9 day overseas trip. I take enough clothes for 9 days because getting laundry done is less predictable, plus I am moving from city to each every 2 or 3 days. Plus these days I have to carry a portable CPAP machine because my doctor thinks I have Sleep Apnea.  Could I get that lot in a carry-on suitcase like I do on short US trips?? What is your advice?\nBrian',0,'1','','',0,2),(84,950,'WBotha','william@interlean.co','http://www.interlean.co','96.251.182.13','2013-05-13 15:23:15','2013-05-13 15:23:15','Brian,\n\nHaving consulted to the industry, I may be able to offer some insight;\n\nThe core value stream the airlines focus upon is limited to the airplane.  They all seek the elusive immediate turn-round.  It is what costs them money and what delivers what they consider to be the service.  Their VSM extends from arrival at the gate to arrival at the next gate.  Therein lies the root cause; improper definition of the service.\n\nYou allude to a score, you get what you measure right?  Guess what airlines measure on delivering the bags to the belt?  Time from cargo door open to FIRST BAGS to the belt!  So what do you think happens?  The ground crews scramble to get the first dolly to the baggage area, they\'ll even just send the one!  That\'s why you will see a spurt of bags appear on the belt, followed by  the rest a lot later.\n\nIf they had to consider the service to be the actual delivery of the passenger to the CURB, rather than the gate, you may see an improvement in the flow through the terminal.\n\nI have even heard passengers described as \'self-sorting baggage.\'\n\nAt the core of the passenger abuse at airports is the multitude of players; stores want you to spend more time browsing so you\'ll make more impulse buys, authorities don\'t care about speed, just their efficiency at ensuring your granny doesn\'t smuggle too much eau-de-toilet onto the plane and the aircrews would love it if you went into a coma for the duration of the flight.\n\nMaybe an air passengers union would be the answer?',0,'1','','',0,0),(85,1028,'Steve Madison','smadison@vitexpackaging.com','','68.115.217.142','2013-06-26 18:00:55','2013-06-26 18:00:55','I am not sure this is a good example of an accounting system creating the problem.  Perhaps it is not understanding the accounting system that is a problem.  By all measures - your improvement in performance would have been noticed as a favorable manufacturing variance in a standard cost system.   To complain about an increase in inventory valuation is often the result of outdated MBA education as opposed to standard cost accounting or even lean accounting.  Standard cost accounting and indeed lean accounting would look at a measure of how this impacts the value stream - inventory turns.  If inventory turns has increased or remained the same then an increase in inventory value is not really a bad thing.  Obviously there is a potential impact on cash flow being if you are cash \"poor\".  You want collections from customers to coincide as closely as possible to cash payments to your vendors.  But even this can often be mitigated as long as borrowing costs are less than the improved production gains.  \n\nI understand your point about measures and what is important to measure.  Telling a production worker to reduce waste by 10% and throwing up a waste chart is meaningless.  Unless you can communicate to that person how to reduce waste and a measure that supports reducing waste then you will fail.  So I agree that all \"measurables\" in manufacturing should be non-financial (unless you are the mint printing money perhaps).  \n\nWhat intrigues me is how you eliminate inventory valuation based on a \"standard\" without wreaking havoc on short-term planning, actual inventory valuation (even standard cost systems require capitalized variance calculations to align with actual costs).  The reason I bring up the actual inventory valuation is that it is quite simple to calculate standard costs and then do a capitalized variance.  Allocating overhead rates for inventory valuation can indeed be quite tricky especially if you have different value streams in your company.  I am guessing that you would value inventory at actual by determining actual costs each month.  This would imply \"pooling\" of inventory costs and being able to recognize different margins on sales of the same product.   \n\nSo I await your next blog to detail how some of this is accomplished.',0,'1','','',0,0),(86,1028,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','72.20.67.198','2013-06-26 23:33:49','2013-06-26 23:33:49','Steve:\n\n\n\nThank you for your thoughtful reply. I do of course see this rather differently from you. I only have a few minutes to reply. \n\n1. Your observation that the people do not understand the accounting is THE issue. By and large people in manufacturing (and other) industries do not understand the accounting because it is complicated, specialized, and very unhelpful to run a lean operation. The spurious product costs, meaningless gross margin against standard, and the baffling absorption and other variances. IMHO the people deserve something better and more helpful to run their business.\n\nI have listed below, some blogs and other information that will shed some more light on this.\n\nStandard Costing issues:  https://maskell.com/?p=927     https://maskell.com/?p=292   http://www.maskell.com/lean_accounting/mindmaps/subpages/do_we_need_product_costing.html\n\nI do not have a blog on inventory valuation because it is rather straightforward, but we do address the various methods in our book \"The Lean Business Management System\".   https://maskell.com/    \n\nhttp://www.amazon.com/Business-Management-Accounting-Principles-Practices/dp/0978976010/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1372284031&sr=8-1&keywords=Lean+business+management+system\n\nOne method is of course to continue to use standard costing, but use it only for what it was designed for - valuing inventory. Do not use it for anything else. Companies making progress with lean however, can use much simpler and more intuitive methods.\n\nGood to hear from you. I would be glad to continue dialogue, if you are interested.\n\nAll the best, \n\nBrian',0,'1','','',0,2),(87,1311,'Keith','keithlorino@att.net','http://www.linkedin.com/keith-lorino/837/839','108.92.61.130','2013-09-04 19:27:19','2013-09-04 19:27:19','I think trying to automate everything can be good or bad. I think some things even like the situation with the web cam, I think should be done manually. I feel it gives it personality, and everyone in the company can receive the meeting invitations at the same time. Just a thought.',0,'1','','',0,0),(88,1311,'Joe','jmflip718@gmail.com','http://www.businessaccountingmastery.com','67.241.182.29','2013-09-05 10:42:01','2013-09-05 10:42:01','Great example, Brian, of how we sometimes lean on technology as a crutch to solve our problems.  Tech seems to be one of those things that we often let the concept of \"ROI\" go by the wayside.  Just because we CAN build a tech tool to do something doesn\'t mean we SHOULD.  Simple is sometimes (often?) better.',0,'1','','',0,0),(89,1311,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','64.134.173.153','2013-09-05 10:55:06','2013-09-05 10:55:06','Thanks for the comments. It seems to me that simple, visual hands-on boards work much better than complex systems because it engages the people. Engages individuals because humans are visual creatures. Engages the team because humans are social creatures. These simple visual methods match the way we work.\n\nThere is a place of IT and a place for visual controls & decision-making. We need to be careful to use both technologies appropriately. Always err on to the visual side first. Use IT when there is a need for significant calculations and standard reporting. IT is good at these things. Use visuals and hand-written stuff when judgment, thought, decision-making is needed, and group activities. \nMake sense?\nBrian',0,'1','','',0,2),(90,1311,'Dan','Robofski@gmail.com','','109.148.5.6','2013-10-29 20:49:48','2013-10-29 20:49:48','Brian, I agree totally with the concept of boards when all can stand around it, how effective do you think a webcam pointing at the board would have been for those that were remote?  I think this is where the desire to use technology comes in to facilitate \'anytime, any place, any device\' access to the material, it does however then usually require more effort and time and I agree you lose the interactivity with the data and it just becomes another excel sheet!',0,'1','','',0,0),(91,1342,'Lennart van Bolderick','lennart@cfogaatbakkies.com','http://www.inventum.com','81.204.219.49','2013-09-26 14:34:05','2013-09-26 14:34:05','Ok,\n\nI agree, but the time put into calculating standards, is never a waste. One needs a proper and detailed Bill of Material and direct labor costs (minutes times actual cost)  (\'the standard\') to run a manufacturing company. AB Costing (anything related to so called indirect costs)  is a waste of time.\n\nI have another \'small\' issue: Our credit line is partly related to our inventory value. I need to send in a detailed inventory list every month. Before I set my  system’s labor and overhead rates to zero I will check what effect this has on my credit line :)\n\nSo to report lean, but not have a decrease in my creditlimit, I make a monthly adjustment to adjust for the \'profit in inventory\', which I estimate in the way you describe. Yes I agree, this is the world upside down, but Creditline is King!\n\nKind regards from Holland',0,'1','','',0,0),(92,1342,'Paul Romano','paul_romano@roadrunner.com','','70.39.176.36','2013-11-22 17:50:05','2013-11-22 17:50:05','The company where I work is not a \"Lean\" operation, nor is there a any momentum to get there... I am most interested in simplifying our internal reporting system to remove the noise that arises when comparing in-month results to P&amp;L COGS, particularly the effects of fixed overhead absorption and re-capitalization/amortization of variances to comply with GAAP accounting (FIFO valuation).\n\nMy thought was to remove all fixed costs (say costs that are less than 70% dependent on production volume) from the standard cost valuation, and use budget/forecast as a control, rather than fixed cost absorption.  Since we turn inventory only every 3+ months, we would have to book adjusting entries to get back to GAAP.  I envision that such a change would entail a re-alignment of \"standard margin analysis\" and re-tooling of incentives that rely on standard margins, such as commissions... and would also have a real impact on lower-of-cost-or-market assessments.\n\nI don\'t see us abandoning standard costs altogether since we have several sites with heavy vertical integration, and tens of thousands of SKU\'s... the simplified value-stream P&amp;L as described above seems more suited for a more simple production process and product offering.\n\nWhat are your thoughts and/or experiences with pursuing this endeavor as described.  Thanks.',0,'1','','',0,0),(93,1342,'NKatko','information@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','74.137.236.158','2013-11-23 16:33:03','2013-11-23 16:33:03','Paul,\nthanks for your comment. I agree with your idea to simplify the process to capitalize labor and overhead. But if your inventory quantities fluctuate significantly month to month, that will not change having to explain the impact of labor and overhead capitalization on profits. \n\nOn a macro level the total amount of manufacturing costs capitalized each month is dependent on the quantity produced vs. quantity shipped. On a micro level it is about the mix of products produced and shipped and the amount of burden each of these products have.\n\nThis is why the real solution to inventory capitalization having material impact on profits is to use lean practices to reduce inventory. Flow &amp; Pull will reduce and stabilize inventory.\n\nLet me know if this helps or not',0,'1','','',92,3),(94,1353,'Danie Vermeulen','Dvermeulen@kaizen.com','http://Www.nz.kaizen.com','122.61.219.150','2013-09-27 22:06:12','2013-09-27 22:06:12','Great case study - well done. I especially like the 5 clear KPI\'s.\nIt is clear that \"Daily Kaizen\" is starting to stick.\nKeep up the good work.\nDanie Vermeulen, \nCEO Kaizen institute NZ',0,'1','','',0,0),(95,1416,'Joe','jmflip718@gmail.com','http://www.businessaccountingmastery.com','64.134.178.27','2013-10-24 02:13:28','2013-10-24 02:13:28','Great takeaways here.  But, for me, the big one is alignment.  Everybody, from top management on down, and all around.  Amazing things can happen when everyone is on the same page and consistent on message.',0,'1','','',0,0),(96,1416,'Paul Todd','paul.todd@gatech.edu','','70.184.6.151','2013-12-03 16:35:12','2013-12-03 16:35:12','What strikes me about this story and others like it is that the traditional accounting reports made it very clear that the product should be dropped, and it certainly would have without the actions taken by Mr. Trnka and his team. \n\nThis clear, by-the-numbers decision has been repeated for 50 years, across many companies and industries, by smart people following conventional wisdom. How many businesses have been outsourced, exited, or otherwise destroyed by this seemingly sound methodology? \n\nThis is the opportunity and the challenge of Lean Accounting - righting a wrong that has been decades in the making.',0,'1','','',0,0),(97,1416,'Lawrence Grasso','grassola@ccsu.edu','','149.152.23.31','2013-12-03 18:04:59','2013-12-03 18:04:59','Dear Vince,  The experience you recount is very encouraging.  I\'ve been to a number of facilities with DOD as heir primary customer.  While they\'ve had great success with kanban and visual controls on the shop floor, their lean progress comes to a screeching halt at the financials.  They are unwilling to expense materials and labor as incurred, citing DOD contracting agreements and/or corporate desire for roll-up of financial results across a number of sites.  I\'d love to hear more details on how you were able to overcome these obstacles, particularly your modification of the pricing model used for government contracts.',0,'1','','',0,0),(98,1478,'Chris Turner','chris@radical-transformation.com','http://radical-transformation.com','96.39.191.102','2013-12-07 16:46:24','2013-12-07 16:46:24','Brian, \n\nI trust all is well with you and yours. Another great article. I really enjoyed reading it and the clarity that it brings about Value Stream Costing.',0,'1','','',0,0),(99,1511,'Robert','robert@gettingtolean.com','http://gettingtolean.com','68.225.219.203','2014-01-08 23:30:13','2014-01-08 23:30:13','Brian,\n\nGreat explanation and the photos were priceless.  Like you, I\'ve used DBTH charts for short term processes, but never long.  Excellent examples.\n\nGoes to prove, once again, that what gets measured gets improved.  BTW, is there a running Action Item sheet that accompanies these charts, or is someone responsible for documenting the problems and their resolutions?\n\nThanks again for sharing.\nRobert',0,'1','','',0,0),(100,1511,'Vinay Kaul','vinay@kaulassociates.com','http://www.lean2sixsigma.co.in','106.198.64.58','2014-02-04 02:43:47','2014-02-04 02:43:47','I have implemented DBTH boards in 3 manufacturing organisations on India. They are all capital goods manufacturers where every order has some part which is customised. Cycle times are often in hours and also varying from order to order. In such situations where there is no discernable cadence, the DBTH board provides a visual and very effective method for controlling the output in every production cell. Couple this with a weekly/ daily gap analysis and you have an excellent foundation for continuous improvement. The throughputs have gone up by over 30% in these companies over a period of 1 year.\nThere is only one key difference over the examples cited by you. I have used the concept of TOC and scheduled only the pacemaker operation for 2 days at a time.',0,'1','','',0,0),(101,1511,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','71.246.7.165','2014-02-04 15:48:39','2014-02-04 15:48:39','Vinay:\nExcellent example. Thank you for your contribution. \nWe also advocate single point scheduling based on the bottleneck operation when the there is a clear constraint. We also use DBR (without the terminology) using kanban squares to ensure the constraint is maximized.\nBrian',0,'1','','',100,2),(102,1547,'Sal Runfola','jags20@optonline.net','','174.44.180.62','2014-02-19 18:57:48','2014-02-19 18:57:48','Brian,\nBack in the 80s, we found ways to eliminate work orders. I can\'t believe that companies are still talking about and using work orders, today. There is an enormous overhead needed to support a work order system that is not always visible. One point that I think should be a motivating factor to eliminating work orders is the huge waste of human work. When you really look at the cost of work order you will be amazed at the human overhead needed to manage this function. If you track the work order process from release to closure (use a VSM method) you can visually see the human waste.\nLike you said, we found ways to trick our system thinking we had used work orders by using back-flushing. We used cell processes and management to report scrap and track serial numbers (medical products) but we used back-flushing at the final process (packing) to report that we built it so we must have used the material in the BOM. The system decremented the inventory for us and updated other production reporting needs. \nWhile there are many valuable benefits of eliminating work orders, another by-product is the eventual elimination of the stockroom where wasted floor space is turned into valuable added value production floor space.\nRegards\nSal',0,'1','','',0,0),(103,1547,'Jim Mowreader','jmowreader@frontier.com','','208.94.82.42','2014-03-03 22:42:50','2014-03-03 22:42:50','Great advice in a mass-production shop; total disaster in job-shop manufacturing - which probably 95 percent of all printing is.',0,'1','','',0,0),(104,1547,'Andrew','af@io.com','http://www.io.com','68.98.22.31','2014-04-13 14:32:22','2014-04-13 14:32:22','Accounting data for labor and material costs for large industrial MTO products (projects) with job costing requirements and component traceability data needs a place to live.  The work order may not need to be on the floor, but it must exist in the information architecture of the enterprise.',0,'1','','',0,0),(105,1576,'Tom Albrecht','toma@aluminumtrailer.com','http://www.aluminumtrailer.com','199.21.199.108','2014-03-31 18:59:38','2014-03-31 18:59:38','Brian:  Enjoyed \"It Irks Me\".   I have observed over time that it seems those involved in strategic roles are better able to \"drive on to knowledge and wisdom” then those focused on tactical or short term objectives.  The observation that regular stand-up meeting offer an opportunity to balance the conversation is right on.\nAt ATC we have developing TWI job instructions.  We applied some of these methods to food processing.  Perhaps we could create a job breakdown for shrimp tail removal.   I wonder what we could learn about this process.\nRegards,\nTom',0,'1','','',0,0),(106,1704,'Jack Kahler','john.a.kahler@us.pwc.com','http://www.pwc.com','198.208.62.254','2014-05-05 22:01:36','2014-05-05 22:01:36','Brian,\n\nGreat discussion, and an excellent topic! Most of the accountants I\'ve worked with are exceptionally hard working, competent professionals who have every intention of doing their best to add value. However, it seems that the accounting profession fosters a very different aproach to quality and efficiency than what we find in traditonal operations functions. Accountants are taught to relentlessly inspect and find errors, but their emphasis is on correction rather than prevention. Root causes are rarely addressed and problems are never eliminated.  There also seems in accounting to be a lack of awareness that business limitations - inefficient workflows, poor data quality, long lead times, etc. - can be addressed and improved by applying Lean techniques.  Barring the technology panacea, accountants usually rely on raising materiality thresholds to hide problems or creating tedious workarounds to muscle through them.  \n\nIn places where we\'ve introduced lean, we have seen tremendous quality and productivity gains once the finance and accounting people set aside their initial reluctance. They start moving quality back to the source, reducing non-value added actitivies, and sharpen their focus on customer value.  But the key to this, as in most lean implementations, is in creating the management systems that will sustain and nurture lean processes.  This requires changing the habits of accounting managers, directors and leaders to a more collaborative, engaged model. This is usually the most difficult step to achieve, yet it\'s the one requirement for locking in lean improvements.\n\nKeep up the good work!\n\nBest regards,\nJack Kahler',0,'1','','',0,0),(107,1714,'Carlos Nunez','Bcnu314@mac.com','','166.137.88.45','2014-05-13 17:06:50','2014-05-13 17:06:50','Nick,\nI\'m not sure if this is an oxymoron or just a downright shame but here\'s my add to your list. \"Process Improvement\" initiatives that are all about cost-cutting with no regard for quality or actually improving a process. The focus on cost reduction alone so often  INCREASES costs and reduces quality in the long run. It hurts to see it happen; and it\'s becoming more common. \nThanks,\nCarlos',0,'1','','',0,0),(108,1735,'Stephane Alby','alby.stephane@gmail.com','','180.52.169.103','2014-05-13 01:05:01','2014-05-13 01:05:01','Hello Brian, great short paper.\n\nA great talk from Y. Morieux on the same... :http://www.ted.com/talks/yves_morieux_as_work_gets_more_complex_6_rules_to_simplify',0,'1','','',0,0),(109,1776,'Jon Hayward-Wright','jshw001@gmail.com','','150.101.223.156','2014-06-18 00:33:55','2014-06-18 00:33:55','The use of the term \"efficiency\" when dealing with people is incorrect, people are not machines, a better term is how \"effective\" they have been, example, a sales man consistently beats all targets even the stretch ones, he is the best of the best. Then his boss finds out he spends 2 days a week on the golf course. If we assume the targets set are stretching, is the sales man \"efficient\" or \"effective\" compared with other sales man?\nEfficiency is best left for engineers when look at how a manufacturing or physical conversion process operates, machines are measured by efficiency, people should be measure by how \"effective\" they are at finding and solving problems.',0,'1','','',0,0),(110,1776,'Steve Dodge','sbdodge@aol.com','','24.52.29.67','2015-01-19 03:44:26','2015-01-19 03:44:26','I agree with the article, labor needs to be addressed from the bottom-up, not top-down.  I agree with Jon, efficiency in machines is known because the standard is fixed.  When dealing with labor, small differences in standard vs. actual is multiplicative and can skew the overall data.  The key is getting out on the floor, reviewing the process, establishing the expectation and holding them too it.  As a bonus; update the standard to reflect reality.',0,'1','','',0,0),(114,1801,'Dave Spann','dwspann_01@yahoo.com','','74.160.177.162','2015-02-03 20:18:28','2015-02-03 20:18:28','Mr. Katko,\nMany thanks for the blog post and I agree with you 100%.  One of the beauties of the \"PULL\" system is the simplicity in which it can implemented.  An effective Kanban board (process) can have the same impact with modest effort.  The Pull System can be used in other areas such operating supplies and materials which is a plus plus.\nHave a great day.',0,'1','','',0,0),(115,1801,'Carl','cfstraussjr@yahoo.com','','73.166.135.254','2015-02-11 13:31:53','2015-02-11 13:31:53','Nick - excellent article!  Inventory days or turns is definitely the main indicator for a company to monitor and pull is definitely the way forward.  Another indicator worth monitoring is inventory aging, which will help to demonstrate problem areas in the upstream processes leading to many inventory problems we experience.',0,'1','','',0,0),(116,1813,'Chris Smith','chris.smith2@milliken.com','','169.146.191.10','2015-03-04 21:38:21','2015-03-04 21:38:21','Would you be interested in speaking on this subject at our annual accounting conference (IMA regional) in Reno Nevada next February?',0,'1','','',0,0),(117,1813,'Ron Ferro','SKFerro@comcast.com','','216.242.176.68','2015-03-05 19:18:35','2015-03-05 19:18:35','Not a big fan for Lean Accounting, I see it more as a marketing thing than any real innovation. Having worked in both, it’s all a matter of company size, product offering and complexity of product. Over the last 15 years, ERP system have become more forgiving and has greater functionality where such things as calculating average cost is greatly simplified. Regardless which environment, it is all “peanut butter” at the journal entry level. Lean Accounting and process costing are both GAAP compliant as long as you capitalize variance and amortize so the methodology is consistent.\nAs we all know, valuating inventory at standard cost is not GAAP. That is why certain costs associated with the production cycle and inventory turns need to be capitalized and amortized. \nLean Accounting comes up short when it comes to product costing analysis for tracking KPI’s, analyzing product specific cost and margin or tracking cost savings.',0,'1','','',0,0),(118,1813,'Paulette Rodriguez, CMA','pdrodriguez3@utep.edu','https://www.linkedin.com/in/paulettecma','129.108.202.65','2015-03-05 23:10:52','2015-03-05 23:10:52','Please keep all of IMA members notified if this speaking engagement gets booked.  I have been asking for more on Lean Accounting, especially since I am trying to introduce it in the classroom.',0,'1','','',116,0),(119,1813,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','72.78.183.142','2015-03-07 17:17:11','2015-03-07 17:17:11','Ron:\nI was surprised at your comments. Unless I misunderstood you, they show little understanding of Lean Management or Lean Accounting. But instead of rebutting your comments I will just reprint an unsolicited testimonial we received a couple of years back from a senior manager who has been using Lean Accounting for several years in a complex aerospace company.\n\n\"I\'ve worked in an organization that applied Brian\'s methodology to value streams that were able to treat labor as a fixed cost. It yielded three measurable wins. \n1) Improved cost and pricing capability which quickly lead to improvements in VS profitability, \n2) Reduced/eliminated the waste of direct labor employees entering data into the ERP system, and \n3) a sustainable lean mindset for all members of the VS.\n\nI think I could write a chapter for a book on each of the 3 items, but the highlight of this transition was item \"3\", the sustainability. Nothing confuses the mindset of the VS members more than telling them that “eliminating waste is a daily mission”, “but keep doing the non-value added reporting tasks because Accounting needs the information”. \nThere may be a need for a few non-value added tasks in the VS due to regulatory constraints, but time keeping was a tough sell to trained VS members. I\'d also add that changing how we treated labor enabled a simple, weekly VS income statement that created real-time feedback on the past week’s VS performance. \nThe weekly VS Income Statement and the improved understanding of capacity for the VS drove the improved pricing capability in item “1”, and so on. It was clear that this was all closely related and would be key to the illusive pursuit of sustainment\n\nDean Cantrill, Vice President, Operations\nCobham Defense Systems Division, Herndon, VA\nJanuary 8, 2013',0,'1','','',117,2),(120,1813,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','173.49.122.238','2015-04-22 17:13:43','2015-04-22 17:13:43','Chris:\nI would be interested in speaking at your IMA Regional conference next year, if the space has not been already taken. \nI am speaking at the IMA Conference in June in Los Angeles\nLet me know.\nBrian\nbmaskell@maskell.com',0,'1','','',116,2),(121,1813,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','173.49.122.238','2015-04-22 17:15:06','2015-04-22 17:15:06','Paulette:\nI am scheduled to speak that IMA Conference in Los Angeles in June some time. I know I am speaking on the Tuesday. \nAre you planning to be there?\nBrian',0,'1','','',118,2),(122,1824,'Gopal','gopal_misra@yahoo.com','http://www.saudifilter.com','178.20.150.162','2015-03-15 09:13:53','2015-03-15 09:13:53','Dear Sir,\n\nIt is an excellent article written by you, it is very brief but covers the importance of Lean very well. I have benefited a lot from your article and looking forward to think and plan accordingly.\n\nBest Regards,\n\nGopal',0,'1','','',0,0),(123,1824,'bob hurley','robertmhurley@gmail.com','','76.182.72.32','2015-03-16 18:12:46','2015-03-16 18:12:46','\"Right on the money\" article, Brian.  I believe that what you say could be applied to anything historical in operations:  MRP, ERP, World Class Manufacturing, etc.\n\nWe do not succeed by plugging in a new computer/software or dropping in a new program from the top.  In the turnarounds I\'ve been involved in (not the financial \'buy and carve up,\' but the \'let\'s improve this operation\' kind), the successes came when we dug in, worked with the folks on the floor, trained, educated, listened, supported, etc.  Interestingly, the reverse is true - in those enterprises where the person in charge looked for a silver bullet, there was failure.\n\nGreat article - look forward to your future blogs.\n\nBest regards,\n\nBob',0,'1','','',0,0),(124,1824,'Accountant Services In Melbourne','chri123na@yahoo.com','http://www.accountingplusconsulting.com.au/','122.168.74.90','2015-03-26 07:42:58','2015-03-26 07:42:58','Thanks for sharing the blogs with us.',0,'1','','',0,0),(125,1824,'yvonne kelleher','yvonneckelleher@gmail.com','','188.141.59.52','2015-06-09 21:11:06','2015-06-09 21:11:06','Do you believe that this is the reason why we hear that large companies are generally more successful in implementing Lean Manufacturing than SMEs?',0,'1','','',0,0),(126,1915,'Eric Reschke','ereschke10@gmail.com','','67.176.26.91','2015-04-21 02:41:51','2015-04-21 02:41:51','nicely written article on the foundations of Lean thinking. I have seen Lean out to work in major Fortune 100 companies and the biggest piece that you touched on here is that leaders must be supportive of this thinking. If not, those further down the vertical line will never be empowered enough to make continuous improvements in their own and everyone -- especially the customer -- loses out and efficiently gained value.',0,'1','','',0,0),(133,1964,'Stefan van Collenburg','stefanvcollenburg@hotmail.com','','193.173.157.194','2015-06-09 11:12:52','2015-06-09 11:12:52','Good article Brian. Very recognizable.',0,'1','','',0,0),(134,1990,'Bill Kluck','leanpro@gmail.com','','8.19.113.13','2015-05-15 15:20:40','2015-05-15 15:20:40','Great article, Brian.  But I could only find the previous one, not all (3) articles you mentioned.  Is this number 2?',0,'1','','',0,0),(135,1990,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','173.49.122.238','2015-05-15 16:23:34','2015-05-15 16:23:34','Bill:\nThanks for the question. I have set up the beginnings of an index for these up-coming posts related to Lean Management Systems. So far there are only 3 publish posts. Two more ready to go and about 25 more to write !!\n\nhttp://www.maskell.com/site/bloglinks/lean_mgmt_system_series/INDEX.pdf\n\nAll the best, Brian',0,'1','','',0,2),(136,1990,'Mike Davis','Mike.davis@mma.ca','http://www.mma.ca','108.183.182.11','2015-05-17 20:03:05','2015-05-17 20:03:05','Excellent review of PDCA just like it was taught to us by Toyoda-Gosei mother company in the late 80s and 90s. Congrats AND thanks from a retired guy who still helps a few people now and then.',0,'1','','',0,0),(137,1990,'Max Blake','max.blake@solvay.com','','63.237.142.177','2015-06-03 17:01:47','2015-06-03 17:01:47','Brian - great article, in my opinion.  I first read this in the Quality Digest Daily of June 3.  Your emphasis on implementing fundamental principles of management and improvement are a breath of fresh air in a world of emphasis on implementing tools.\nWe continue to be subjected to the \"expert driven\" process you describe, whether it\'s outside or inside consultants.  However, at our site we are striving to implement a site-wide Management System that focuses on leadership (set the direction, communicate with all, model the desired behaviors), problem solving (PDSA based process), organization (everyone knows their position and roles &amp; responsibilities), involvement (everyone is a problem solver for the work they do), and capability building (train people to do their jobs, educate people to grow their capabilities).  We do not call this \"Lean\" because it has nothing to do with the current, popularized, shallow representation of the Toyota Way.  It does have everything to do with deeply implementing a management system that is suitable to our business and processes.  Our management system relies on the very same fundamentals that you describe in this article, except you call it a Lean Management System.  My question is, when will the use of the term \"Lean\" cease to be used to promote the management method that is fundamental and timeless?',0,'1','','',0,0),(138,2089,'Reka','excelantotech@gmail.com','http://www.excelanto.com/','49.207.181.97','2016-04-04 10:50:05','2016-04-04 10:50:05','Great Article..It was very informative..I need more details from your side..include some tips..I am working in <a href=\"http://www.excelanto.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">Erp In Chennai</a>',0,'1','','',0,0),(139,2092,'Peter Liepmann','pliepm1@my.wgu.edu','','174.135.124.145','2015-07-16 16:45:16','2015-07-16 16:45:16','Great instructional video! \n\n You have some typos in your images- \"Why create a value stream Organization<strong>s</strong>\"  \nShould be \n\"Why create a value stream Organization?\"  or\n\"Why create value stream Organizations?\" \n\nIt detracts from your message!',0,'1','','',0,0),(140,2106,'Jim Gatto','jim.gatto@robinsonfans.com','','24.154.230.20','2015-07-20 12:41:23','2015-07-20 12:41:23','Great post.  What are the other 4 articles regarding the lean management system you referenced in your first paragraph?',0,'1','','',0,0),(141,2106,'Lorenzo del Marmol','ldm@leansixsigmabelgium.com','http://www.leansixsigmabelgium.com','109.128.195.79','2015-11-09 11:29:31','2015-11-09 11:29:31','Hi,\n\nGreat article. Regarding point 4. \"Build Customer Value\" what is the best tool/approach to capture and manage customer value &amp; insight? \n\nThanks in advance for your answer. \n\nKind regards,\n\nLorenzo del Marmol - Partner\nwww.leansixsigmabelgium.com',0,'1','','',0,0),(142,2106,'BMaskell','bmaskell@maskell.com','http://www.maskell.com','95.147.209.114','2016-01-21 00:08:10','2016-01-21 00:08:10','Jim:\nI am sorry for the delayed reply. I have not looked back on this blog for a while.\nThe 4 articles are prior blogs on the topics of Lean Management System. You can identify them by seeing the round circle and the letter B or A at the top of the circle. These relate to the diagram \"Lean Management System\". If you click the Lean Management System diagram you will get a bigger picture.\nAll the best,\nBrian',0,'1','','',140,2),(143,2166,'Oxychem Supplies','athenadalisay123@gmail.com','http://oxychemsupplies.com.ph/','114.108.243.180','2016-03-10 06:04:40','2016-03-10 06:04:40','OXYCHEM Supplies and Equipment was established in 2014, a sister company of OXYCHEM Corporation, that provides comprehensive list of cleaning supplies and equipment for small and medium industries. We carry a wide variety of specialized cleaning supplies and equipment to answer every cleaning and sanitation requirements of most businesses.\nThroughout the years, OXYCHEM Supplies and Equipment expanded its services and products by offering cleaning supplies and equipment to be able to serve bigger markets which include institutional and industrial sectors.',0,'1','','',0,0),(152,2337,'Rosemary Fullerton','rrfprof@hotmail.com','','107.194.97.100','2015-11-20 02:03:02','2015-11-20 02:03:02','Hi Brian,\nI really like this.  It\'s succinct and yet covers the main points of lean accounting. Do you have this in a PDF or Word file, so that I could share it with my executive MBA students? \n\nI hope all is going well. \n\nRosemary',0,'1','','',0,0),(153,2337,'Susana Santos','susana.santos@manitowoc.com','','89.155.44.97','2015-11-22 14:06:32','2015-11-22 14:06:32','Hello Brian.\nVery good article. \nI must share and agree with you that controllers and accountants must be off the \"accountant department\". It´s the only way to really understand the activity and have a full vision of the business. Sometimes for accountants and controllers number and variances are just that \"number\". But in fact, we must have in our companies \"Real Numbers\"!',0,'1','','',0,0),(154,2349,'Robert','Robert@gettingtolean.com','http://Gettingtolean.com','70.209.101.129','2015-12-13 19:15:49','2015-12-13 19:15:49','Brian, I continue to be amazed at your ability to capture complex ideas in writing.  Your gift is rare.\n\nI have a question for you: In the early stages of a lean transformation, what accounting measures do you use? Second question: when do you begin to transition to lean accounting methods? \n\n Many thanks for a brilliantly written post on lean accounting.\nRobert',0,'1','','',0,0),(159,2489,'Marc Bach','mbabon@leancoach.cat','','62.57.102.170','2016-05-05 18:26:03','2016-05-05 18:26:03','Dear mr. Maskell,\n\nVery interesting and helpful post. I hope to see sth similar one day in a construction site.\n\nMarc Bach',0,'1','','',0,0),(160,2489,'Mr Maskell','Armando_Hernandez@jafra.com.mx','','201.151.198.226','2016-05-05 20:43:07','2016-05-05 20:43:07','How to implement a Day-By-The-Hour chart?, another questions, how measure the accuaracy to inventory? what tools use it?\nThank you, regards',0,'1','','',0,0),(161,2489,'Marcus Haugen','marcusils@yahoo.com','','24.31.214.217','2016-05-05 21:47:18','2016-05-05 21:47:18','Brian.... hope this finds you well! I have a client in WI going through this paradigm right now! The true believers know you speak the truth!',0,'1','','',0,0),(162,2489,'Marcus Haugen','marcusils@yahoo.com','','24.31.214.217','2016-05-05 21:48:26','2016-05-05 21:48:26','Brian~! Hope this finds you well! The true believers know you speak the truth!',0,'1','','',0,0),(163,2489,'Debbie','debbobjoel@gmail.com','','116.15.176.45','2016-05-05 23:30:51','2016-05-05 23:30:51','Lean helps us to identify system problems and effectiveness of the systems and processes based on evidence and best practices. Hence Lean is not just about efficiency but it is also about effectiveness. In healthcare people take a long time to come to terms about lean because of the much emphasis on efficiency and without considering effectiveness .',0,'1','','',0,0),(164,2489,'Robert Redanz','Rob.Redanz@gmail.com','','64.233.172.161','2016-05-06 00:48:49','2016-05-06 00:48:49','I\'d there a meaningfull relation between production rate and change over time. The longer your Chang overs  the larger your campaigns have to be.',0,'1','','',0,0),(165,2489,'You\'re my Lean Consultant','rod.mccallum@rpbsafety.com','','96.88.147.244','2016-05-06 12:32:06','2016-05-06 12:32:06','Rubbish. Efficiency is simply a measurement that you take to see if the operators are slacking. We operate lean (within reason) and that\'s what we use if for. Also we use it to bonus our people if they work harder, they get a kickback of the savings. You do not have to use it for anything else, but you absolutely HAVE TO know what your performance is. I don\'t care what anyone says. For us, it doesn\'t say anything about stashing product all over the place to keep operators busy. You can use a different tool for that, and if the floor has too many people? Bingo, that\'s it. You\'ve got the idea.',0,'1','','',0,0),(166,2489,'Perrin','xperrin@xp-consulting.fr','','80.215.110.62','2016-05-07 06:24:30','2016-05-07 06:24:30','Great article Brian.\nI wrote two articles on my blog a few months ago that bring complementary ideas. The first one is about a frequent misunderstanding about SMED and the pursuit of change over time reduction : http://www.consulting-xp.com/blog/?p=363\nThe second one is about a frequent misunderstanding of the muda of waiting and overproduction : http://www.consulting-xp.com/blog/?p=546\nXavier',0,'1','','',0,0),(167,2489,'Sean Driscoll','sean.driscoll@gbssolutions.net','http://www.gbssolutions.net','172.72.147.197','2016-05-07 13:13:12','2016-05-07 13:13:12','Hi Brian,\n\nEnjoyed reading your post.  For me it illustrates the misuse of metrics.  While very few metrics do well all by themselves there are a few that even balanced with others will still drive the wrong behaviors.  Holding people to efficiencies will more likely have an affect on how important other aspects of the business are viewed; safety, maintenance, cleanliness, etc.  \n\nWhen trying to use efficiency as a metric it\'s difficult to \"nail down\" an appropriate standard.  The more complex the operations the more creative the industrial engineers seem to get in devising a formula for establishing a standard.  I am a proponent of making labor a fixed cost over a longer period of time.  Any company should know if the month/quarter/year is not going well as it is happening.  Besides, Do the people creating value every really cause less demand for the product or service?',0,'1','','',0,0),(169,2489,'Mike Clayton','mclayton200@gmail.com','','72.208.120.216','2016-05-07 20:04:58','2016-05-07 20:04:58','As usual, \"it depends.\"  If the production operation can create reliability problems if standard work is changed or cheated to meet quotas or bonus you will get problems that may end up in court as customers are injured (as in automotive products.)\nIf you are picking grapes manually that\'s another story. \nDo you want to develop shop floor TEAMS that cooperate on improvements or shop floor wars where \"rate busters\" are punished.  The stopwatch people were banned or all  work stopped if they looked at their watches in many union shops as I remember, so the unions were destroyed by \"right to work\" laws in retaliation.   Sweat shops get very high efficiencies but usually with high turnover, so if job requires training if can be costly to \"punish slackers.\"',0,'1','','',165,0),(170,2589,'The Answer to Culture Change: Everyday Management Tactics &#8211; Medi-Cafe','','https://cafepharmablog.wordpress.com/2019/03/13/the-answer-to-culture-change-everyday-management-tactics/','192.0.113.204','2019-03-13 13:46:25','2019-03-13 13:46:25','[&#8230;] the initial phase of the work, with help from Lean consultant Brian Maskell, who pioneered the&nbsp;box score in the manufacturing industry. The intensive work with the value prototype team included two site visits to introduce the tools [&#8230;]',0,'1','The Incutio XML-RPC PHP Library','pingback',0,0),(171,2589,'The Answer to Culture Change: Everyday Management Tactics &laquo; Knowledge Space','','https://knowledgespaceblog.wordpress.com/2019/03/13/the-answer-to-culture-change-everyday-management-tactics/','192.0.87.235','2019-03-13 17:17:44','2019-03-13 17:17:44','[&#8230;] in the initial phase of the work, with help from Lean consultant Brian Maskell, who pioneered the box score in the manufacturing industry. The intensive work with the value prototype team included two site visits to introduce the tools [&#8230;]',0,'1','The Incutio XML-RPC PHP Library','pingback',0,0),(172,2589,'Is there a simple formula for sustainable quality improvement? &#8211; Best Care','','https://www.bestcare.org.za/2019/03/26/is-there-a-simple-formula-for-sustainability/','41.204.202.49','2019-03-27 06:17:39','2019-03-27 06:17:39','[&#8230;] management includes a focus on cost through the use of a “box score” (a concise performance dashboard in the form of a spreadsheet updated weekly) and a visual [&#8230;]',0,'1','The Incutio XML-RPC PHP Library -- WordPress/4.9.10','pingback',0,0);
